// Committed, tracked file — this is what makes `xcodegen generate` succeed on
// a fresh clone with no local setup at all (project.yml's configFiles points
// here). The safe empty defaults below mean the app builds and links fine
// without real Plaid credentials; Plaid calls just fail until you configure
// real ones.
//
// To develop against real Plaid Sandbox (or Production) credentials, copy
// Config/Plaid.local.xcconfig.example to Config/Plaid.local.xcconfig
// (gitignored — never commit real credentials) and fill in PLAID_CLIENT_ID
// and PLAID_SANDBOX_SECRET from the Plaid dashboard
// (https://dashboard.plaid.com/team-settings/keys). The #include? below
// pulls that file in if it exists and its assignments override the defaults
// declared above them (xcconfig: the last assignment of a given setting
// wins) — if it doesn't exist, #include? is a silent no-op and the empty
// defaults stand.
//
// PLAID_SANDBOX_SECRET is the Sandbox environment's secret only — this story
// (reservoir-adq.6.1) is Sandbox-only. Production switching is a separate
// story (reservoir-adq.6.2) and will introduce its own secret handling.
//
// OAuth-institution redirects use a universal link
// (https://johnpease.github.io/oauth), not a custom URL scheme — Plaid's
// dashboard requires an https redirect URI. The domain is hardcoded in
// PlaidServiceLive.swift and must be registered as an "Allowed redirect
// URI" in the Plaid dashboard, and its Associated Domains entitlement
// (Reservoir.entitlements) must list the same host. No per-developer
// config needed here.
//
// These values are embedded into the built app's Info.plist and are
// readable by anyone with the .app bundle — acceptable only under this
// app's accepted risk posture (personal, sideloaded, single-user, not
// distributed). Do not commit real credentials — put them in
// Plaid.local.xcconfig, not here.

PLAID_CLIENT_ID =
PLAID_SANDBOX_SECRET =
PLAID_PRODUCTION_SECRET =

#include? "Plaid.local.xcconfig"
